  "description": "There is a political dimension that rarely gets named directly, even though it quietly structures almost every argument we have about policy, justice, and the future. It is not left versus right, nor radical versus conservative. It is a measure of how much homogeneity an ideology requires in order to function at all.\nSome ideologies only work if the world behaves “the same way everywhere.” Others can tolerate difference, drift, rupture, and unevenness without losing coherence. This difference shows up in moral language, policy preferences, and in the statistical and dynamical assumptions the ideology quietly depends on.\n",
  "name": "2025-12-12, Measuring ideologies",
